"43030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44333"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive breathlessness and dry cough. She describes nine days of preceding generalised fatigue, headaches, and runny nose. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals generalised expiratory wheeze and widespread rhonchi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows patchy consolidation in the right lower lobe. Sputum microscopy and culture are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Intravenous ceftriaxone plus azithromycin","Oral doxycycline","Intravenous piperacillin/tazobactam"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of atypical pneumonia, including a prodrome of constitutional symptoms, dry cough, and relatively mild clinical features. The presence of extra-pulmonary symptoms (fatigue, headache) and negative sputum culture are characteristic. Based on vital signs and clinical features, this represents mild disease with a low SMART-COP score.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for mild atypical pneumonia in an otherwise healthy patient. It provides excellent coverage against common atypical organisms including \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ELegionella species\u003C/em\u003E. Oral clarithromycin can also be used as an alternative first-line treatment for atypical pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E targets typical bacterial pathogens such as \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E but has poor activity against atypical organisms. It would be appropriate for typical community-acquired pneumonia but not in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not appropriate as it does not cover atypical organisms. Additionally, the mild nature of illness does not warrant intravenous therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone plus azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E combination therapy would be indicated for moderate to severe community-acquired pneumonia, typically with SMART-COP score \u0026gt;2, but is excessive for this mild presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous piperacillin/tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe hospital-acquired pneumonia or in immunocompromised patients. It is not indicated for mild community-acquired pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atypical pneumonia typically presents with a prodrome of extra-pulmonary symptoms, dry cough, and mild clinical features","Doxycycline is first-line treatment for mild atypical pneumonia in immunocompetent patients","Disease severity assessment using SMART-COP score guides the choice between oral and intravenous antibiotics"],"references":["Adler, N., et al., Adherence to Therapeutic Guidelines for patients with CommunityAcquired Pneumonia in Australian Hospitals. Clinical Medicine Insights: Circulatory, Respiratory and Pulmonary Medicine, 2014. 8: p. 17 - 20. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25249765/","Fine, M.J., et al., A prediction rule to identify low-risk patients with community-acquired pneumonia. New England Journal of Medicine, 1997. 336(4): p. 243-250. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8995086/","Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd., Community Acquired Pneumonia in Adults. Therapeutic Guidelines, 2019. [Available at:https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=community-acquired-pneumonia-adults\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e59]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84890"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"646"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84890"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T16:56:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T16:57:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonym